<section class="hero hero--transform" aria-label="Hero" role="region">
  {%- comment -%}
    Hero transformation animation. Three pre-composed 16:9 frames cross-fade
    in sequence: customer's photo → soft watercolour portrait → finished
    canvas hanging on a styled home wall. Frames are baked with a cream
    negative-space on the left two-thirds so the overlay copy stays legible
    throughout the cycle. The animation settles longest on the canvas-on-
    wall state — that's the emotional payoff. prefers-reduced-motion drops
    to a static canvas-on-wall image (skips the animation entirely).
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="hero__media hero__media--stack" aria-hidden="false">
    {%- comment -%}
      Each frame ships two crops. Desktop loads the wide 1920×1072 frame
      (subject in right third, cream negative space on the left for the
      overlay copy column). Mobile loads a tight 1170×1071 crop where
      the subject is centered with cream padding on both sides — looks
      properly composed on a phone instead of touching the screen edge.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 760px)" srcset="{{ 'hero-transform-1-photo-mobile.webp' | asset_url }}">
      <img class="hero-frame hero-frame--1"
           src="{{ 'hero-transform-1-photo.webp' | asset_url }}"
           alt="Your pet's photo"
           loading="eager" fetchpriority="high"
           width="1920" height="1072">
    </picture>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 760px)" srcset="{{ 'hero-transform-2-watercolour-mobile.webp' | asset_url }}">
      <img class="hero-frame hero-frame--2"
           src="{{ 'hero-transform-2-watercolour.webp' | asset_url }}"
           alt="Soft watercolour portrait of your pet"
           loading="eager"
           width="1920" height="1072">
    </picture>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 760px)" srcset="{{ 'hero-transform-3-canvas-mobile.webp' | asset_url }}">
      <img class="hero-frame hero-frame--3"
           src="{{ 'hero-transform-3-canvas.webp' | asset_url }}"
           alt="Pet portrait canvas hanging on a wall at home"
           loading="eager"
           width="1920" height="1072">
    </picture>
  </div>

  <div class="hero__layout container">
    <div class="hero__content">
    {%- comment -%}
      Above-the-fold hero copy paints immediately — no data-reveal.
      The hero already runs its own staged photo→watercolour→canvas
      cross-fade, and a 0.6–0.9s opacity-0 stagger on top of that left
      the eyebrow + headline invisible during the photo phase (the
      asset's lightest, lowest-contrast frame).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <p class="hero__eyebrow">{{ section.settings.eyebrow | default: 'From your phone to your wall' }}</p>
    <h1 class="hero__title">{{ section.settings.heading | default: 'They deserve a spot on the wall.' }}</h1>
    <p class="hero__sub">{{ section.settings.subheading | default: 'Museum-grade canvas, gallery-wrapped and built to outlast the wall it hangs on.' }}</p>

    <div class="hero__cta-group">
      <a href="{{ section.settings.cta_url | default: '/pages/create' }}" class="btn btn--canvas-frame btn--large">
        <span class="btn__canvas-inner">
          {{ section.settings.cta_label | default: 'Create My Portrait' }}
          <svg class="btn__arrow" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M5 12h14M13 5l7 7-7 7"/>
          </svg>
        </span>
      </a>
      {%- if section.settings.secondary_cta_label != blank -%}
        <a href="{{ section.settings.secondary_cta_url }}" class="btn btn--outline btn--large">
          {{ section.settings.secondary_cta_label }}
        </a>
      {%- endif -%}
    </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  /* Hero transformation — overrides the regular .hero pattern just for this
     section so the rest of the theme's hero CSS doesn't fight us. */
  .hero--transform { position: relative; overflow: hidden; isolation: isolate;
                     background: #FAF8F5; min-height: 448px; }
  .hero--transform .hero__media--stack {
    position: absolute; inset: 0;
    display: block;
    /* Fade the bottom of the photo into the section cream so the
       console-table edge in frame 3 (canvas-on-wall) doesn't read as
       a hard horizontal line cutting under the CTA. The fade reveals
       the section's #FAF8F5 base, so the headline column hands off
       cleanly into the trust bar with no seam. */
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, #000 0%, #000 70%, transparent 100%);
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, #000 0%, #000 70%, transparent 100%);
  }
  .hero-frame {
    position: absolute; inset: 0;
    width: 100%; height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover; object-position: center right;
    will-change: opacity, transform;
  }

  /* Top dark gradient — keeps the site header (white logo, white nav,
     outline CTA) legible against the light watercolour and canvas-on-
     wall frames. Top stop is dense so the white nav/logo reads cleanly,
     then eases out steeply so the gradient is fully transparent well
     above the subject's face — no visible bottom edge crossing the dog. */
  .hero--transform::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; right: 0;
    height: 110px;
    background: linear-gradient(to bottom,
      rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.58) 0%,
      rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.4) 40%,
      rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.08) 78%,
      rgba(28, 28, 28, 0) 100%);
    z-index: 1; pointer-events: none;
  }

  /* Left cream wash — anchors the headline column with reliable
     contrast across all three frames. Frames A/B already have cream
     in this zone so the wash is invisible on them; Frame C (canvas on
     wall, with the eucalyptus vase + console pushing toward center-
     left) gets a meaningful legibility lift in the column where the
     subhead and CTA wrap. Stops at ~58% so the visual on the right
     never feels veiled.

     Earlier the wash held opacity longer in the lower half of the
     section but faded in over a 96px mask near the top — that left
     the eyebrow zone (~168–220px from the top) sitting on a near-
     transparent wash during the photo phase. The wash now starts at
     the top of the section with a much shorter 48px feather, holds
     0.94+ opacity through 35% of the column, and rolls off slower
     so a light-cream subject in the right two-thirds (Frame 1's
     phone photo) can't bleed into the headline column. */
  .hero--transform::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute; top: 0; bottom: 0; left: 0;
    width: 62%;
    background: linear-gradient(
      to right,
      rgba(250, 248, 245, 0.98) 0%,
      rgba(250, 248, 245, 0.94) 35%,
      rgba(250, 248, 245, 0.7) 60%,
      rgba(250, 248, 245, 0.25) 82%,
      rgba(250, 248, 245, 0) 100%
    );
    /* Top fade is now short (48px) so the wash reaches the eyebrow
       with full opacity. The dark header gradient (110px tall, fades
       out by 78%) sits over the top portion of the wash, so the
       upper edge still hands off cleanly to the header chrome
       without a visible horizontal seam. */
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, transparent 0%, #000 48px, #000 100%);
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, transparent 0%, #000 48px, #000 100%);
    z-index: 1; pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    /* On mobile the visual stacks above the copy, so the left cream
       wash isn't needed (and would tint the dog). */
    .hero--transform::after { display: none; }
  }
  /* Initial states — frame 1 visible, others hidden. */
  .hero-frame--1 { opacity: 1; }
  .hero-frame--2 { opacity: 0; }
  .hero-frame--3 { opacity: 0; }

  /* 7-second loop. Settles longest on frame 3 (the canvas on the wall),
     which is the emotional payoff and the clearest value-prop frame. */
  @keyframes hero-frame-1 {
    0%, 18%   { opacity: 1; }
    25%, 100% { opacity: 0; }
  }
  @keyframes hero-frame-2 {
    0%, 18%   { opacity: 0; }
    25%, 43%  { opacity: 1; }
    50%, 100% { opacity: 0; }
  }
  @keyframes hero-frame-3 {
    0%, 43%   { opacity: 0; }
    50%, 92%  { opacity: 1; }
    98%, 100% { opacity: 0; } /* brief fade to dark before re-loop to frame 1 */
  }
  .hero--transform .hero-frame--1 { animation: hero-frame-1 7.5s ease-in-out infinite; }
  .hero--transform .hero-frame--2 { animation: hero-frame-2 7.5s ease-in-out infinite; }
  .hero--transform .hero-frame--3 { animation: hero-frame-3 7.5s ease-in-out infinite; }

  /* Layout wrapper — keeps content respecting the 1280px container while
     the visual stays full-bleed underneath. Desktop uses a two-column
     grid that anchors the headline stack to the left negative-space
     column of every baked frame; the right column stays empty so the
     dog/canvas (already composed on the right third of each frame)
     reads cleanly. */
  .hero--transform .hero__layout {
    position: relative; z-index: 2;
    min-height: inherit;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
  @media (min-width: 761px) {
    .hero--transform { min-height: clamp(368px, 42vw, 480px); }
    .hero--transform .hero__layout {
      grid-template-columns: minmax(360px, 540px) 1fr;
      align-items: center;
      column-gap: 32px;
    }
  }

  .hero--transform .hero__content {
    /* Asymmetric padding for VISUAL balance, not mathematical: the
       dark header gradient (height 110px, sits over the top of the
       hero) consumes the upper part of the section, so symmetric
       padding leaves the eyebrow looking crowded against the gradient
       and the CTA floating in roomy cream below. Adding the gradient
       height to the top padding equalises the visible cream space
       above the eyebrow and below the CTA. */
    padding: clamp(168px, 15vw, 220px) 0 clamp(60px, 7vw, 96px);
    max-width: 540px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__cta-group {
    justify-content: center;
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-body, sans-serif);
    font-size: var(--text-xs, 0.75rem);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-accent, #8B7D6B);
    margin: 0 0 14px;
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__title {
    font-family: var(--font-heading, serif);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5.5vw, 3.6rem);
    font-style: italic; font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-ink, #1C1C1C);
    line-height: 1.05;
    /* `auto` on left/right keeps the constrained block centered in the
       column. Was 0 0 16px which silently left-anchored the title and
       was making the centered text inside look misaligned vs the CTA. */
    margin: 0 auto 16px;
    max-width: 520px;
    /* Hairline halo so dark serif copy stays crisp over the soft
       watercolour bleed without feeling shadowed. */
    text-shadow: 0 1px 0 rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6);
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__sub {
    font-family: var(--font-body, sans-serif);
    font-size: clamp(0.95rem, 1.6vw, 1.075rem);
    color: var(--color-ink, #1C1C1C);
    line-height: 1.55;
    margin: 0 auto 28px;
    max-width: 460px;
    text-shadow: 0 1px 0 rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__cta-group {
    display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 12px;
    margin-bottom: 18px;
  }
  /* Override the global `.hero .btn--primary` glass-on-dark treatment —
     this hero is light, so the primary CTA needs to read as a solid
     dark button. Same visual identity as the rest of the site's
     primary CTAs (cart checkout, sticky-add-to-cart, etc.). */
  .hero--transform .hero__cta-group .btn--primary {
    background: var(--color-primary, #2F2F2A);
    color: #fff;
    border: 1px solid transparent;
    backdrop-filter: none;
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: none;
    box-shadow: 0 6px 18px rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.18);
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__cta-group .btn--primary:hover {
    background: var(--color-primary-dk, #3D3D36);
    box-shadow: 0 8px 22px rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.24);
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__cta-group .btn--outline {
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6);
    color: var(--color-ink, #1C1C1C);
    border: 1px solid rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.18);
    backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
  }
  .hero--transform .hero__cta-group .btn--outline:hover {
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.85);
    border-color: rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.32);
  }
  /* Step strip — the reassurance line now carries the customer journey
     ("Upload → Create custom portrait → Hang"). Slight tracking + medium weight gives
     it a step-indicator feel without competing with the eyebrow's full
     small-caps treatment. The arrow characters inherit the same colour
     so the whole line reads as a single, scannable strip. */
  .hero--transform .hero__reassurance {
    font-size: var(--text-xs, 0.78rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: rgba(28, 28, 28, 0.78);
    line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  /* Mobile — uses the dedicated 1170×1071 mobile crops (loaded via
     <picture>) where the subject is pre-centered with cream padding
     on both sides. Container aspect matches the asset, so cover is a
     no-op and we just render the asset as composed. The image takes
     ~42% of viewport so the headline + CTA stay above the fold. */
  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .hero--transform {
      min-height: 0;
      display: flex; flex-direction: column;
    }
    .hero--transform::before { display: none; }
    .hero--transform .hero__media--stack {
      /* Container aspect deliberately tighter than the asset (1170x1071,
         which has 165px cream padding baked in on each side) so the
         cover-crop trims that padding off and the dog reads as the full
         hero subject instead of floating in side margins. Square ratio
         keeps the image presence without pushing the CTA below the fold
         on the average phone viewport. */
      position: relative; aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
      width: 100%; height: auto;
      overflow: hidden;
    }
    .hero-frame--3 { object-position: center center; }
    /* Frames 1 and 2 mobile assets are cropped to their painted/photo
       content (818x1071, aspect 0.764) — no blank cream margins. Asset
       aspect is narrower than the container's 4/5 (0.8), so cover
       scales by width: the full asset width fills the viewport with a
       tiny vertical crop. The dog lands at its natural ~38% of the
       cropped asset = ~38% of viewport. Can't push it further right
       without re-exposing the blank cream margins that read as
       "cropped" — the source photo composes the dog left-of-frame. */
    .hero-frame--1 { object-position: center center; }
    .hero-frame--2 { object-position: center center; }
    .hero-frame__stage { bottom: 12px; right: 12px; padding: 6px 10px; gap: 8px; }
    .hero-frame__stage-label { font-size: 11px; }
    .hero--transform .hero__layout {
      display: block; padding: 0;
    }
    .hero--transform .hero__content {
      padding: 24px var(--gutter, 16px) 28px;
      max-width: none;
    }
    /* Eyebrow — softer tracking + slightly smaller so it reads as a
       label rather than a competing headline. */
    .hero--transform .hero__eyebrow {
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.12em;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    /* Title — bumped up so the headline owns the section. Tighter
       line-height so the two-line wrap feels intentional. */
    .hero--transform .hero__title {
      font-size: clamp(1.95rem, 8.5vw, 2.5rem);
      line-height: 1.08;
      margin: 0 auto 12px;
      max-width: 22ch;
    }
    .hero--transform .hero__sub {
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.5;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
      max-width: 36ch;
    }
    .hero--transform .hero__cta-group {
      margin-bottom: 12px;
    }
    /* CTA — was full-width edge-to-edge which read as oversized on
       phones. Pin to a sane width so it feels like a button, not a
       banner, and trim the vertical padding so the text-to-padding
       ratio matches the rest of the type stack. */
    .hero--transform .hero__cta-group .btn {
      width: auto;
      min-width: 220px;
      max-width: 320px;
      padding: 14px 24px;
      font-size: 0.92rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    }
    .hero--transform .hero__reassurance {
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      opacity: 0.7;
    }
    .hero-frame__stage-dot { width: 5px; height: 5px; }
  }

  /* Reduced motion — settle on the canvas-on-wall frame, no cycling.
     The product story is still told (just without the transformation). */
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .hero-frame--1, .hero-frame--2 { opacity: 0 !important; animation: none !important; }
    .hero-frame--3 { opacity: 1 !important; animation: none !important; }
    .hero-frame__stage { display: none; }
  }
</style>

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "Hero Transformation",
  "tag": "section",
  "settings": [
    { "type": "paragraph", "content": "Animated three-frame hero. The frames live in assets/ — replace `hero-transform-1-photo.webp`, `hero-transform-2-watercolour.webp`, and `hero-transform-3-canvas.webp` to swap the visual." },
    { "type": "text", "id": "eyebrow", "label": "Eyebrow", "default": "From your phone to your wall" },
    { "type": "text", "id": "heading", "label": "Heading", "default": "They deserve a spot on the wall." },
    { "type": "textarea", "id": "subheading", "label": "Subheading", "default": "Museum-grade canvas, gallery-wrapped and built to outlast the wall it hangs on." },
    { "type": "text", "id": "cta_label", "label": "Primary CTA label", "default": "Create My Portrait" },
    { "type": "url", "id": "cta_url", "label": "Primary CTA URL" },
    { "type": "text", "id": "secondary_cta_label", "label": "Secondary CTA label (optional)" },
    { "type": "url", "id": "secondary_cta_url", "label": "Secondary CTA URL" },
    { "type": "text", "id": "reassurance", "label": "Reassurance text below CTAs", "default": "Upload → Create custom portrait → Hang" }
  ],
  "presets": [{ "name": "Hero Transformation" }]
}
{% endschema %}
